  1. In general, there are three purposes for a layer:

  1. To Display the Data: pattern detection on spot gross structure, local structure, and outliers.

  2. To Display a Statistical Summary of the Data: displaymodel predictions in the context of the data.

  1. Showing the data helps us imrpove the model

  2. Showing the model helps us reveal subtleties of the data that might otherwise miss.

  3. Summaries are usually drawn on top of the data.

  1. To Add Additional Metadata: context, annotations, and references.

  1. A metadata layer displays background context, annotations that help to give meaning to the raw data, or fixed references that aid comparisons across panels.

  2. Metadata can be useful in the background and foreground.

  1. A map is often used as a background layer with spatial data.

  2. Background metadata should be rendered so that it does not interfere with your perception of the data, so is usually displayed underneath the data and formatted so that it is minimally perceptible.

  1. Other metadata is used to highlight important features of the data such as render inflection points or outliers so that they pop out at the viewer. This should be the very last layer drawn.

3.2 Basic Plot Types

  1. Basic plot type geoms are the fundamental building blocks of ggplot2.

  1. Most of these geoms are associated with a named plot: when that geom is used by itself in a plot, that plot has a special name.

  2. Each of these geoms is two dimensional and requires both \(x\) and \(y\) aesthetics.

  3. All of these geoms understand color and size aesthetics, and the filled geoms (bar, tile, polygon) and also understand fill.

  1. Basic Plot Types Geoms
  1. geom_area(): draws an area plot, which is a line plot filled to the y-axis (filled lines).
  1. Multiple groups will be stacked on top of each other.
  1. geom_bar(stat="identity"): makes a bar chart.

  1. Need stat="identity" as the default stat autmatically counts the values (so is essentially a 1d geom).

  2. The identity stat leaves the data unchanged.

  3. Multiple bars in the same location will be stacked on top of one another.

  1. geom_line(): makes a line plot.

  1. The group aesthetic determines which observations are connected.

  2. geom_line() connects points from left to right.

  3. geom_path() connects points in the order they appear in the data.

  4. Both geom_line() and geom_path() understand the aesthetic linetype, which maps a categorical variable to solid, dotted and dashed lines.

  1. geom_point(): produces a scatterplot.
  1. geom_point() also understands the shape aesthetic.
  1. geom_polygon(): draws polygons, which are filled paths.

  1. Each vertex of the polygon requires a separate row in the data.

  2. It is often useful to merge a data frame of polygon coordinates with the data just prior to plotting.

  1. geom_rect(), geom_tile(), geom_raster(): draw rectangles.

  1. geom_rect() is parametrised by the four corners of the rectangle, xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax.

  2. geom_tile() is exactly the same but parametrised by the center of the rect and its size, x, y, width, height.

  3. geom_raster() is a fast special case of geom_tile() used when all the tiles are the same size.

df=data.frame(
  x=c(3,1,5),
  y=c(2,4,6),
  label=c("a","b","c")
)

p=ggplot(df, aes(x,y,label=label))+
  labs(x=NULL, y=NULL)+ # Hide axis label
  theme(plot.title=element_text(size=12)) # Shrink plot title
p+geom_point()+ggtitle("point")

p+geom_text()+ggtitle("text")

p+geom_bar(stat="identity")+ggtitle("bar")

p+geom_tile()+ggtitle("raster")

p+geom_line()+ggtitle("line")

p+geom_area()+ggtitle("area")

p+geom_path()+ggtitle("path")

p+geom_polygon()+ggtitle("polygon")

3.2.1 Exercises

  1. What geoms would you use to draw each of the following named plots?

  1. Scatterplot: geom_point()

  2. Line Chart: geom_line()

  3. Histogram: geom_histogram()

  4. Bar Chart: geom_bar(stat="identity")

  5. Pie Chart: geom_bar(stat="identity")

# Create Data
data <- data.frame(
  group=LETTERS[1:5],
  value=c(13,7,9,21,2)
)

# Basic piechart
ggplot(data, aes(x="", y=value, fill=group)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", width=1, color="white") +
  coord_polar("y", start=0) +
  
  theme_void() # remove background, grid, numeric labels

  1. What is the difference between geom_path() and geom_polygon()? What is the difference between geom_path() and geom_line()?

Difference between geom_path() and geom_polygon(): geom_path() connects points in the order they appear in the data while geom_polygon() draws polygons, which are filled paths.

Difference between geom_path() and geom_line(): geom_line() connects points from left to right while geom_path() connects points in the order they appear in the data.

  1. What low-level geoms are used to draw geom_smooth()? What about geom_boxplot() and geom_violin()?

geom_smooth(): geom_line()

geom_boxplot: geom_rect()

geom_violin(): geom_polygon()

3.3 Labels ~~

  1. geom_text(): main tool to add labels at the specified x and y positions.
  1. geom_text() has the most aesthetics of any geom.
  1. family: gives the name of a font.
  1. There are only three fonts that are guarantted to work everywhere “sans” (the default), “serif”, or “mono”.
df=data.frame(x=1, y=1:3, family=c("sans", "serif", "mono"))

ggplot(df, aes(x,y))+
  geom_text(aes(label=family, family=family))

  1. fontface: specifies the face: “plain” (the default), “bold”, or “italic”.
df=data.frame(x=1, y=3:1, face=c("plain", "bold", "italic"))

ggplot(df, aes(x,y))+
  geom_text(aes(label=face, fontface=face))

  1. hjust and vjust: adjust the alighment of text.

  1. hjust takes values “left”, “center”, “right”, “inward”, “outward”.

  2. vjust takes values “bottom”, “middle”, “top”, “inward”, “outward”.

  3. The default alignment is centered.

  4. One of the most useful alignments is “inward”: it aligns text towards the middle of the plot.

df=data.frame(
  x=c(1,1,2,2,1.5),
  y=c(1,2,1,2,1.5),
  text=c("bottom-left", "bottom-right", "top-left", "top-right", "center")
)

ggplot(df, aes(x,y))+
  geom_text(aes(label=text))

ggplot(df, aes(x,y))+
  geom_text(aes(label=text), vjust="inward", hjust="inward")

# Note: hjust and vjust are aesthetics meaning they can be put in aes() function but they do not have to be in aes() function like the case above.
  1. size: controls the font size.

  1. ggplot2 uses mm rather than the usual points (pts). This makes it consistent with other size units in ggplot2.

  2. There are 72.27 pts in a inch, so to convert from points to mm, just multiply by \(72.27/25.4\).

  1. angle: specifies the rotation o f the text in degrees.
  1. geom_text() has three parameters. Unlike aesthetics, these only take single values, so they must be the same for all labels.
  1. nudge_x, (2) nudge_y: nudge the text a little horizontally or vertically.
df=data.frame(trt=c("a","b","c"), resp=c(1.2,3.4,2.5))



ggplot(df, aes(resp, trt))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_text(aes(label=paste0("(",resp,")")))+
  xlim(1,3.6)

ggplot(df, aes(resp, trt))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_text(aes(label=paste0("(",resp,")")), nudge_y=-0.25)+
  xlim(1,3.6) # manually tweaked the x-axis to make sure all the text fit on the plot

  1. check_overlap=TRUE: overlapping labels will be automatically removed.
  1. Algorithm: labels are ploted in the order they appear in the data frame; if a label would overlap with an existing point, it is omitted.
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy))+
  geom_text(aes(label=model))+
  xlim(1,8)

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy))+
  geom_text(aes(label=model), check_overlap=TRUE)+
  xlim(1,8)

  1. geom_label(): a variation on geom_text(). It draws a rounded rectangle behind the text. It is useful for adding labels to plots with busy backgrounds.
label=data.frame(waiting=c(55,80), eruptions=c(2,4.3), label=c("peak one","peak two"))

ggplot(faithfuld, aes(waiting, eruptions))+
  geom_tile(aes(fill=density))+
  geom_label(data=label, aes(label=label))

  1. Challenges of Labelling Data

  1. Text does not affect the limits of the plot. A label has an absolute size, regardless of the size of the plot.

  2. If you want to label many points, it is difficult to avoid overlaps. check_overlap=TRUE offers little control over which labels are removed.

  1. If all else fails, you may need to manually label points in a drawing tool.
  1. Text labels can also serve as an alternative to a legend. This usually makes the plot easier to read as it puts the labels closer to the data.
  1. The directlabels package provides a number of tools to add labels directly to the plot.
ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy, color=class))+
  geom_point()

ggplot(mpg, aes(displ, hwy, color=class))+
  geom_point(show.legend = FALSE)+
  directlabels::geom_dl(aes(label=class), method="smart.grid") # smart.grid is a reasonable place to start for scatterplots

3.4 Annotations

  1. Annotations add metadata to your plot. But metadata is just data, so you can use:

  1. geom_text(): add text descriptions or to label points. Labelling outliers and other important points is very useful.

  2. geom_rect(): highlight interesting rectangular regions of the plot.

  1. geom_rect() has aesthetics xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax.
  1. geom_line(), geom_path(), geom_segment(): to add lines.
  1. All these geoms have an arrow parameter, which allows you to place an arrowhead on the line. Create arrowheads with arrow(), which has arguments angle, length, ends, type.
  1. geom_vline(), geom_hline(), geom_abline(): allow you to add reference lines (somtimes called rules), that span the full range of the plot.
  1. Either put annotations in the foreground (using alpha if needed so you can still see the data), or in the background.
  1. The default is in the background.
# Time series of unemploytment
ggplot(economics, aes(date, unemploy))+
  geom_line()

  1. The use -Inf and Inf as positions. These refer to the top and bottom (or left and right) limits of the plot.
# Annotate the time series with which president was in power at the time

presidential=subset(presidential, start>economics$date[1])

ggplot(economics)+
  geom_rect(
    aes(xmin=start, xmax=end, fill=party),
    ymin=-Inf, ymax=Inf, alpha=0.2, data=presidential
  )+
  geom_vline(
    aes(
      xintercept=as.numeric(start)
    ),
    data=presidential,
    color="grey50", alpha=0.5
  )+geom_text(
    aes(x=start, y=2500, label=name),
    data=presidential,
    size=3, vjust=0, hjust=0, nudge_x=50
  )+geom_line(aes(date, unemploy))+
  scale_fill_manual(values=c("blue", "red"))

# Add a single annotation to a plot: have to create a one row data frame

yrng=range(economics$unemploy)
xrng=range(economics$date)

caption=paste(strwrap("Unemployment rates in the US have varied a lot over the year", 40), collapse="\n")


ggplot(economics, aes(date, unemploy))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_text(
    aes(x,y,label=caption),
    data=data.frame(x=xrng[1],y=yrng[2],caption=caption),
    hjust=0, vjust=1, size=4
  )

# Easier to use the annotate() helper function which creates the data frame for you

ggplot(economics, aes(date, unemploy))+
  geom_line()+
  annotate("text", x=xrng[1], y=yrng[2], label=caption, hjust=0, vjust=1, size=4)

  1. Annotations, particularly reference lines, are also useful when comparing groups across facets.
# Without reference lines
ggplot(diamonds, aes(log10(carat), log10(price)))+
  geom_bin2d()+
  facet_wrap(~cut, nrow=1)

# With reference lines

mod_coef=coef(lm(log10(price)~log10(carat), data=diamonds))

ggplot(diamonds, aes(log10(carat), log10(price)))+
  geom_bin2d()+
  geom_abline(intercept=mod_coef[1], slope=mod_coef[2], color="white", size=1)+
  facet_wrap(~cut, nrow=1)

3.5 Collective Geoms

  1. Geoms can be roughly divided into two types:
  1. Individual Geom: draws a distinct graphical object for EACH observation (row).
  1. For exaple, the point geom draws one point per row.
  1. Collective Geom: displays ultiple observations with one geometric object.

  1. For example, this may be a result of a statistical summary, like a boxplot.

  2. Or this may be fundamental to the display of the geom, like a polygon.

  1. Lines and Paths: fall somewhere in between individual geom and collective geom:
  1. Each line is composed of a set of straight segments, but each segment represents two points.
  1. Group Aesthetic: control the assignment of observations to graphical elements.
  1. By default, the group aesthetic is mapped to the interaction of all discrete variables in the plot.

  1. This often partitions the data correctly.

  2. If it does NOT partition the data correctly or when NO discrete variable is used in a plot, need to explicitly definthe grouping structure by mapping group to a variable that has a different value for each group.

3.5.1. Multiple Groups, One Aesthetic

  1. Separate data into groups, but render them in the same way. That is, want to be able to distringuish individual subjects, but NOT identify them.

  1. Commonly used in longitudinal studies with many subjects.

  2. Plots are often called Spaghetti Plots.

ggplot(Oxboys, aes(age, height, grou=Subject))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_line()

  1. If a group is NOT defined by a single variable, but instead by a combination of multiple variables, use interaction() to combine them, e.g. aes(group=interaction(school_id, student_id)).

3.5.2 Different Groups on Different Layers

  1. Plot summaries that use different levels of aggregation: one layer might display individuals, while another displays the overall summary.
  1. Put Grouping in the Top Layer (i.e. ggplot() layer): grouping in the top layer controls BOTH the display of the geoms, and the operation of the stats: one statistical transformation if run for EACH group. Setting group in the top layer will aply to all subsequent layers.
ggplot(Oxboys, aes(age, height, group=Subject))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_smooth(method="lm", se=FALSE)+
  ggtitle("Wrong Graph")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

  1. Put Grouping in a Specific Subsequent Layer: putting group to a specific subsequent layer then it will apply only to that layer.
ggplot(Oxboys, aes(age, height))+
  geom_line(aes(group=Subject))+
  geom_smooth(method="lm", size=2, se=FALSE)+
  ggtitle("Correct Graph")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

# Note: there is no discrete variable in the plot (both weight and height are cts) so the default grouping variable will be a constant and we get one smooth.

3.5.3 Overriding the Default Grouping

  1. Some plots have a discete x scale, but you still want to draw lines connecting across groups.

  1. This is the strategy used in interaction plots, profile plots, and parallel coordinate plot, among others.

  2. For discrete x, to overlay lines that connect each unique x value, we need to override the grouping.

3.6 Surface Plots

  1. ggplot2 does NOT support true 3d surfaces but it does support many common tools for representing ed surfaces in 2d.

  1. Contours

  2. Coloured Tiles

  3. Bubble Plots: work better with fewer observations

ggplot(faithfuld, aes(eruptions, waiting))+
  geom_contour(aes(z=density, color=..level..))

ggplot(faithfuld, aes(eruptions, waiting))+
  geom_raster(aes(fill=density))

small=faithfuld[seq(1, nrow(faithfuld), by=10),]

ggplot(small, aes(eruptions, waiting))+
  geom_point(aes(size=density), alpha=1/3)+
  scale_size_area()
